"NoVA." That's what they call it. Or "NoVA," if you're feeling particularly… casual. It’s a region, you see, a collection of counties and cities clinging to the western and southern edges of [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.). Not that it needs my approval. It's already established.

Look at the pictures. The top left, that's [Tysons station](/Tysons_station) on the [Silver Line](/Silver_Line_(Washington_Metro)). Cold, functional. Then there's [The Pentagon](/The_Pentagon), a monument to organized paranoia. [Reston](/Reston,_Virginia) is there, a planned community, all neat lines and enforced pleasantries, bisected by the [Dulles Toll Road](/Virginia_State_Route_267). And [Old Town Alexandria](/Old_Town_Alexandria), trying to look historic, I suppose. Finally, [Mount Vernon](/Mount_Vernon), of course. Everyone knows Mount Vernon.

They call it the "New Dominion." A rather optimistic moniker, wouldn't you say? As if anything truly new can arise from such predictable soil.

### Geography

The counties that make up this… entity… they’re part of the larger [Washington–Baltimore combined statistical area](/Washington%E2%80%93Baltimore_combined_statistical_area). A sprawling, interconnected mess. The population, as of 2023, is a staggering 3,257,133. Over a third of [Virginia](/Virginia)'s entire population. It's the most populous region in Virginia, and in the entire [Washington metropolitan area](/Washington_metropolitan_area). Go figure.

The communities here are woven into the fabric of the Washington metropolitan area, and by extension, the wider [Washington–Baltimore combined statistical area](/Washington%E2%80%93Baltimore_combined_statistical_area). It’s curious, isn't it, how the job base here dwarfs even that of [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.) itself, and the [Maryland](/Maryland) suburbs. And the income levels? Astronomical. Three of the top ten highest-income counties in the nation, according to some survey. Makes you wonder what they're *doing* all day.

Transportation. They’ve got the essentials: two major airports, [Ronald Reagan Washington National](/Ronald_Reagan_Washington_National_Airport) and [Dulles International Airport](/Dulles_International_Airport). The [Washington Metro](/Washington_Metro) snakes through it, a metallic serpent. The [Virginia Railway Express](/Virginia_Railway_Express) tries to connect the scattered populace. [Transit buses](/Transit_bus) lumber along. They’ve even got bicycles, for those who enjoy the illusion of personal freedom. And, of course, an endless web of [Interstate highways](/Interstate_highway) and expressways.

And [The Pentagon](/The_Pentagon). Headquarters of the [U.S. Department of Defense](/United_States_Department_of_Defense). The second-largest office building in the world. A testament to bureaucracy and the art of looking busy. Then there's the [George Bush Center for Intelligence](/George_Bush_Center_for_Intelligence) in [Langley](/Langley,_Virginia), the nerve center of the [Central Intelligence Agency](/Central_Intelligence_Agency). The [United States Patent and Trademark Office](/United_States_Patent_and_Trademark_Office) in [Alexandria](/Alexandria,_Virginia). And a constellation of [aerospace manufacturing](/Aerospace_manufacturer), [consulting firms](/Consulting_firm), and [defense industry](/Arms_industry) companies, all feeding at the trough of the [U.S. federal government](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States).

As for tourism? [Arlington National Cemetery](/Arlington_National_Cemetery). [Fredericksburg and Spotsylvania National Military Park](/Fredericksburg_and_Spotsylvania_National_Military_Park). [Manassas National Battlefield Park](/Manassas_National_Battlefield_Park). [Mount Vernon](/Mount_Vernon). The [National Museum of the Marine Corps](/National_Museum_of_the_Marine_Corps). The [National Museum of the United States Army](/National_Museum_of_the_United_States_Army). The [Udvar-Hazy Center of the National Air and Space Museum](/Steven_F._Udvar-Hazy_Center). The [Marine Corps War Memorial](/Marine_Corps_War_Memorial). And, naturally, bits of the [Appalachian Trail](/Appalachian_Trail), [Great Falls Park](/Great_Falls_Park), [Old Town Alexandria](/Old_Town_Alexandria), [Prince William Forest Park](/Prince_William_Forest_Park), and the edges of [Shenandoah National Park](/Shenandoah_National_Park). A rather grim collection, if you ask me.

### Etymology

They capitalize the "N" in "Northern Virginia." Apparently, it's a proper noun, not just a direction. How quaint.

The term "Northern Virginia" wasn't always in use. In the early days, it was the "Northern Neck of Virginia." A vast tract of land between the [Potomac](/Potomac_River) and [Rappahannock](/Rappahannock_River) rivers, stretching west to some arbitrary line. The [Fairfax line](Fairfax_Stone), they called it. Surveyed in 1746, marking the boundary between the springs of the Potomac and Rappahannock. This Northern Neck encompassed 5,282,000 acres. Larger than some entire states.

### History

#### Colonial period

The initial settlement at [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia) in 1607 was a distant precursor. The land that would become "Northern Virginia" was part of a grant from King [Charles II of England](/Charles_II_of_England) in 1649, while he was still in exile. Loyal supporters were named, among them Thomas Culpeper.

Later, in 1673, a new charter was issued to [Thomas Lord Culpeper](/Thomas_Colepeper,_2nd_Baron_Colepeper) and [Henry Earl of Arlington](/Henry_Bennet,_1st_Earl_of_Arlington). Culpeper, appointed Royal Governor of Virginia from 1677 to 1683, was more interested in his land holdings than governing. He arrived late, left early, and apparently had a penchant for misappropriating funds. His descendants, and others, eventually managed the properties.

It wasn't until 1736 that [Thomas Fairfax, 6th Lord Fairfax of Cameron](/Thomas_Fairfax,_6th_Lord_Fairfax_of_Cameron) – "Lord Fairfax" to the colonists – solidified his claim. His lands, the "Northern Neck," were defined by the rivers. By 1746, the western boundary was surveyed, creating a grant of 5,282,000 acres. This included what are now 22 counties in Virginia and West Virginia.

Lord Fairfax, a bachelor, became a notable figure. [Fairfax County](/Fairfax_County,_Virginia) was named for him in 1742. He resided at "Belvoir" and later built a hunting lodge, "Greenway Court," near the [Blue Ridge Mountains](/Blue_Ridge_Mountains). It was there he met a young, energetic [George Washington](/George_Washington), whom he employed to survey his western lands. Fairfax remained neutral during the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) and died in 1781.

#### Statehood and Civil War

After the Revolution, [George Washington](/George_Washington), a Virginian, became the first president of the new United States. He was a proponent of [Alexandria](/Alexandria,_Virginia), a port city on the [Potomac River](/Potomac_River).

The nation's capital, initially in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia), moved to [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.) in 1800. The federal district included territory ceded by Maryland and Virginia. Alexandria, on the Virginia side, felt disenfranchised. In 1846, the U.S. Congress [retroceded](/District_of_Columbia_retrocession) the land south of the Potomac back to Virginia. This area became [Alexandria County](/Alexandria_County,_D.C.), later renamed [Arlington County](/Arlington_County,_Virginia).

The growing divide between the North and South over [slavery](/Slavery), [states' rights](/States%27_rights), and economic issues culminated in the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War). Virginia seceded and joined the [Confederate States of America](/Confederate_States_of_America), with its capital in [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia). Maryland remained with the Union.

Northern Virginia, situated between the two capitals, became a battleground. The [Army of Northern Virginia](/Army_of_Northern_Virginia) was the Confederacy's primary eastern force. Numerous battles were fought here. [John Singleton Mosby](/John_S._Mosby), a Confederate partisan, operated in the region, engaging Union forces.

The war's aftermath saw many schools, roads, and parks named for Confederate figures.

Virginia itself fractured during the war. Western counties, largely opposed to secession, formed the new state of [West Virginia](/West_Virginia) in 1863. This region, geographically separated from Richmond by the [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains), had little in common with the eastern, slave-dependent areas. A provisional government of Virginia was headquartered in Union-controlled Alexandria. Counties like Arlington, Clarke, Fairfax, Frederick, Loudoun, Shenandoah, and Warren, though voting to remain in the Union, eventually became part of West Virginia.

The formation of West Virginia meant a portion of Lord Fairfax's original land grant, the area now known as the [Eastern Panhandle of West Virginia](/Eastern_Panhandle_of_West_Virginia), was ceded.

#### 20th century

The region's economy was profoundly shaped by the [Cold War](/Cold_War). The [Department of Defense](/United_States_Department_of_Defense)'s reliance on technology companies fueled growth and urban development. After 1991, it rebranded itself as the "[Silicon Valley](/Silicon_Valley)" of the [Eastern United States](/East_Coast_of_the_United_States). It was here that the Internet was first commercialized, with many early [Internet service providers](/Internet_service_provider) establishing headquarters.

[MAE-East](/MAE-East), a crucial early Internet interconnection point, was established in [Ashburn](/Ashburn,_Virginia) in the 1990s. This infrastructure laid the groundwork for the current data center boom.

#### 21st century

The early 2000s saw the merger of [AOL](/AOL) and [Time Warner](/Time_Warner), a late gasp of the [dot-com bubble](/Dot-com_bubble). The bubble's burst led to a significant increase in office vacancy rates. However, post-[September 11 attacks](/September_11_attacks), defense spending surged, revitalizing the region. The [Afghanistan](/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%932021)) and [Iraq](/Iraq_War) wars further boosted growth as federal contracts multiplied.

### Regional organizations

The [Northern Virginia Regional Commission (NVRC)](/Northern_Virginia_Regional_Commission) is a council of thirteen local governments. It provides services and coordinates regional efforts on environmental, transportation, housing, planning, military, and human services matters. It operates as Virginia's Planning District 8.

The [Metropolitan Washington Council of Governments (MWCOG)](/Metropolitan_Washington_Council_of_Governments) is another significant regional body, comprising 22 local governments and legislative representatives. It serves as a forum for discussing and addressing regional issues like the environment, transportation, public safety, housing, planning, and economic development. Its Transportation Planning Board is the federally designated [metropolitan planning organization](/Metropolitan_planning_organization) for the area.

### Demographics

As of April 2020, Northern Virginia had a population of 3,197,076, representing about 37 percent of Virginia's total. The region forms a significant portion of the [Washington-Arlington-Alexandria, DC-VA-MD-WV Metropolitan Statistical Area](/Washington_Metropolitan_Area) and the [Washington-Baltimore-Arlington, DC-MD-VA-WV-PA Combined Statistical Area](/Baltimore%E2%80%93Washington_metropolitan_area).

The "central" counties and independent cities – Arlington, Fairfax, Fauquier, Loudoun, Prince William, Stafford, and Alexandria, Fairfax, Falls Church, Manassas, Manassas Park, and Fredericksburg – housed the majority of the population. The more exurban or developing counties – Clarke, Culpeper, Frederick, Madison, Rappahannock, Spotsylvania, Warren, and Winchester – contained the remainder. Some definitions also include King George and Orange counties, though they are not officially part of the Washington Metropolitan Area.

The racial and ethnic composition, according to the [2020 U.S. census](/2020_United_States_census), shows a diverse population. White alone, not Hispanic or Latino, makes up the largest group across most jurisdictions, but significant Hispanic or Latino, Black or African American, and Asian populations are present, particularly in the more urbanized areas. Overall, Northern Virginia is approximately 51.2% White, 17.4% Hispanic, 16.3% Asian, 14.1% Black, and 2.4% Other.

The region is home to substantial communities of [Korean Americans](/Korean_Americans), [Vietnamese Americans](/Vietnamese_Americans), [Bangladeshi Americans](/Bangladeshi_Americans), [Chinese Americans](/Chinese_Americans), [Filipino Americans](/Filipino_Americans), [Russian Americans](/Russian_Americans), [Arab Americans](/Arab_Americans), [Palestinian Americans](/Palestinian_Americans), [Uzbek Americans](/Uzbek_Americans), [Afghan Americans](/Afghan_Americans), [Ethiopian Americans](/Ethiopian_Americans), [Indian Americans](/Indian_Americans), [Iranian Americans](/Iranian_Americans), [Thai Americans](/Thai_Americans), and [Pakistani Americans](/Pakistani_Americans). [Annandale](/Annandale,_Virginia), [Centreville](/Centreville), [Chantilly](/Chantilly,_Virginia), and [Fairfax City](/Fairfax,_Virginia) are notable for their large [Korean American](/Korean_American) populations. [Falls Church](/Falls_Church,_Virginia) has a significant Vietnamese American community, and there's a small [Tibetan American](/Tibetan_Americans) presence.

The Hispanic population is diverse, including [Salvadorans](/Salvadorans), [Peruvians](/Peruvians), [Puerto Ricans](/Puerto_Ricans), [Cubans](/Cubans), [Bolivians](/Bolivians), [Mexicans](/Mexicans), and [Colombians](/Colombians). Arlington is a center for the largest [Bolivian](/Bolivians) community in North America. These immigrants contribute to various sectors like transportation, small businesses, hospitality, construction, and cleaning.

For those born in the U.S. within the four largest counties, a significant portion (60.5%) originate from the [South](/Southern_United_States), with 21.0% from the [Northeast](/Northeastern_United_States), 11.5% from the [Midwest](/Midwestern_United_States), and 7.0% from the [West](/Western_United_States). Virginia itself, categorized as part of the [Southern United States](/Southern_United_States), accounts for 33.7% of these native-born residents.

#### Educational attainment

The core jurisdictions of Northern Virginia – Alexandria, Arlington, Fairfax, Loudoun, and Prince William – boast a highly educated populace. Over 55.5% of residents aged 25 and older hold a bachelor's degree or higher. This statistic is comparable to [Seattle](/Seattle), a city known for its educated population. Arlington, in particular, has a high percentage of graduate/professional degree holders (34.3%), significantly exceeding the national average.

#### Affluence

[Reston](/Reston,_Virginia), a [planned community](/Planned_community), exemplifies the region's affluence. Northern Virginia is recognized for its relative wealth within the [Washington metropolitan area](/Washington_metropolitan_area). Notably, [Stafford County](/Stafford_County,_Virginia) is one of the few counties nationwide where Black households have a higher median income than White households. Several counties and cities here exceed a [median household income](/Median_household_income) of $100,000.

However, this affluence comes with a high cost of living, diminishing the actual purchasing power. [Loudoun County](/Loudoun_County,_Virginia) and [Arlington County](/Arlington_County,_Virginia) consistently rank high for the concentration of 25- to 34-year-olds earning $100,000+.

The region's retail landscape reflects this affluence. [Tysons Galleria](/Tysons_Galleria) and [Tysons Corner Center](/Tysons_Corner_Center) are prominent shopping destinations. Tysons Galleria, in particular, has been described as the "[Rodeo Drive](/Rodeo_Drive)" of the [East Coast](/East_Coast_of_the_United_States). Luxury real estate firms, like [Sotheby's](/Sotheby%27s) International Realty, have established offices here to cater to the high-end market.

#### Crime

Despite its affluence, Northern Virginia maintains relatively low homicide rates compared to the state average. The "Crime in Virginia 2021" report indicates this trend. However, a 2009 report highlighted concerns about anti-gang measures potentially displacing gang members to less stringent areas. While violent crime rates have decreased, the region has also been identified as an emerging hub for teen [sex trafficking](/Sex_trafficking), with gangs finding it more profitable than drug or weapons sales. Fairfax County, in particular, is noted for having one of the lowest crime rates among the nation's largest jurisdictions.

### Economy

Former Governor [Bob McDonnell](/Bob_McDonnell) famously dubbed Northern Virginia the "economic engine of the state." As of 2007, the region's office market was substantial, exceeding that of Washington, D.C., and its Maryland suburbs in square footage. Construction continued, particularly in the Dulles Corridor.

The unemployment rate in Northern Virginia has consistently been lower than the national average. Even during economic downturns, the region has shown resilience, creating jobs while other areas lost them. Fairfax County, for instance, has been a magnet for [creative-class](/Creative_class) workers.

#### Internet

Northern Virginia is a critical nexus for the nation's Internet traffic. [Loudoun County](/Loudoun_County,_Virginia), in particular, is a global hub for data centers, handling a significant portion of internet traffic. It boasts the world's largest data center market by capacity and is experiencing rapid growth. This concentration of data centers has a substantial impact on energy consumption. Major cloud providers, like Amazon, have a significant presence here, with a large percentage of their servers located in the region.

#### Federal government

The [federal government](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States) is a dominant employer. Northern Virginia hosts the headquarters of key intelligence agencies like the [Central Intelligence Agency](/Central_Intelligence_Agency) and the [Department of Defense](/United_States_Department_of_Defense) at [the Pentagon](/The_Pentagon). Other significant federal facilities include [Fort Myer](/Fort_Myer), [Fort Belvoir](/Fort_Belvoir), [Marine Corps Base Quantico](/Marine_Corps_Base_Quantico), the [FBI Academy](/FBI_Academy), and the [U.S. Patent and Trademark Office](/United_States_Patent_and_Trademark_Office). Government contracting is a vital component of the regional economy, with Arlington noted for its high weekly wages for federal contractors.

Several agencies with substantial budgets or employee numbers are located here, including the [Defense Logistics Agency](/Defense_Logistics_Agency), [National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency](/National_Geospatial-Intelligence_Agency), [National Reconnaissance Office](/National_Reconnaissance_Office), and the [Transportation Security Administration](/Transportation_Security_Administration).

#### Notable companies

Northern Virginia is home to numerous major corporations. [Capital One Financial](/Capital_One) has its headquarters in [Tysons, Virginia](/Tysons,_Virginia). [AES Corporation](/AES_Corporation), a global power company, is based in [Arlington County, Virginia](/Arlington_County,_Virginia). [Boeing](/Boeing) has a significant presence, with its headquarters now in [Crystal City, Virginia](/Crystal_City,_Virginia). [Booz Allen Hamilton](/Booz_Allen_Hamilton) and [CACI International](/CACI) are major players in information technology services. [General Dynamics](/General_Dynamics) and [Northrop Grumman](/Northrop_Grumman) are prominent in the [aerospace and defense](/Defense_contractor) sector. [Hilton Worldwide](/Hilton_Worldwide) has its global headquarters in [Tysons, Virginia](/Tysons,_Virginia).

The region is also a hub for major private companies. [Bechtel](/Bechtel), a global engineering and construction giant, is headquartered in [Reston, Virginia](/Reston,_Virginia). [Mars, Incorporated](/Mars,_Incorporated), the confectionery and pet food conglomerate, has its headquarters in [McLean, Virginia](/McLean,_Virginia). [Verisign](/Verisign), responsible for managing the [.com](/.com) and [.net](/.net) top-level domains, is also based here.

### Attractions

The region offers a variety of attractions, from shopping to historical sites. Large malls like [Potomac Mills](/Potomac_Mills_(shopping_mall)) and [Tysons Corner Center](/Tysons_Corner_Center) draw visitors. Civil War battlefields, such as those at [Manassas](/Manassas,_Virginia) and [Fredericksburg](/Fredericksburg,_Virginia), are significant historical sites. [Old Town Alexandria](/Old_Town_Alexandria) charms with its historic architecture, shops, and restaurants.

Outdoor enthusiasts can enjoy the [Washington and Old Dominion Rail Trail](/Washington_%26_Old_Dominion_Railroad_Regional_Park), the [Mount Vernon Trail](/Mount_Vernon_Trail), and activities along the [Potomac River](/Potomac_River), including kayaking and rock climbing at [Great Falls Park](/Great_Falls_Park). [Mount Vernon](/Mount_Vernon), George Washington's plantation, remains a popular destination. Stafford County holds historical significance with [Ferry Farm](/Ferry_Farm), George Washington's boyhood home, and [Chatham Manor](/Chatham_Manor), a Civil War-era site.

[Arlington National Cemetery](/Arlington_National_Cemetery) offers a solemn tribute. The [Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center](/Steven_F._Udvar-Hazy_Center), an annex of the [National Air and Space Museum](/National_Air_and_Space_Museum), houses aviation and space artifacts. [Wolf Trap National Park for the Performing Arts](/Wolf_Trap_National_Park_for_the_Performing_Arts) is a venue for concerts and performances.

### Politics

Northern Virginia has undergone a significant political transformation. Historically dominated by [Conservative Democrats](/Conservative_Democrat) and the [Byrd Organization](/Byrd_Organization), the region has increasingly shifted towards the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) in the 21st century.

#### 21st-century politics

The region's voting patterns in presidential elections show a clear Democratic trend. [Fairfax County](/Fairfax_County,_Virginia), the state's most populous county, has voted Democratic in recent presidential elections, a departure from its historical leanings. This shift has been crucial in tipping statewide elections for Democrats like [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama), [Jim Webb](/Jim_Webb), and [Tim Kaine](/Tim_Kaine). The growing suburban and exurban areas, once reliably Republican, have become more competitive, with Democrats making gains.

The [7th](/Virginia%27s_7th_congressional_district), [8th](/Virginia%27s_8th_congressional_district), [10th](/Virginia%27s_10th_congressional_district), and [11th](/Virginia%27s_11th_congressional_district) congressional districts are located within Northern Virginia, and are currently represented by Democrats.

The region's closer proximity to Washington, D.C., a higher concentration of transplants from other regions, and growing ethnic diversity contribute to its more liberal political landscape compared to the rest of Virginia, which is often perceived as more traditionally Southern. This has led to debates and rhetoric about "real Virginia" versus the "new Virginia" of the suburbs.

Social issues, such as same-sex marriage, also show a divide, with Northern Virginia demonstrating significantly higher support for legalization compared to the rest of the state.

### Culture

Given its proximity to the capital, many Northern Virginians engage with the cultural offerings of [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.). The [Kennedy Center](/John_F._Kennedy_Center_for_the_Performing_Arts) is a popular venue. Locally, [Wolf Trap National Park for the Performing Arts](/Wolf_Trap_National_Park_for_the_Performing_Arts) hosts concerts. Other popular venues include [Jiffy Lube Live](/Jiffy_Lube_Live), [EagleBank Arena](/EagleBank_Arena), and [Capital One Arena](/Capital_One_Arena) in D.C. The [Smithsonian](/Smithsonian_Institution) museums are easily accessible.

Shopping is a significant cultural activity. [Tysons Corner Center](/Tysons_Corner_Center) and [Tysons Galleria](/Tysons_Galleria) are major retail hubs. [Tysons](/Tysons,_Virginia) itself is a substantial business district. Other malls like [Springfield Mall](/Springfield_Mall_(Virginia)), [Fair Oaks Mall](/Fair_Oaks_Mall), and outlet malls like [Potomac Mills](/Potomac_Mills_(shopping_mall)) cater to various consumer needs.

### Recreation

Northern Virginia offers a range of recreational activities, including extensive biking and walking trails like the [Washington and Old Dominion Rail Trail](/Washington_%26_Old_Dominion_Railroad_Regional_Park) and the [Mount Vernon Trail](/Mount_Vernon_Trail). The [Northern Virginia Swim League](/Northern_Virginia_Swim_League) is a prominent youth sports organization. The [National Capital Area Council](/National_Capital_Area_Council) and the [National Capital Soccer League](/National_Capital_Soccer_League) serve local communities.

### Transportation

Northern Virginia's transportation infrastructure is complex and often strained.

#### Airports

The region is served by [Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport](/Ronald_Reagan_Washington_National_Airport), the busiest in the metropolitan area, and [Dulles International Airport](/Dulles_International_Airport), a major international gateway and hub for [United Airlines](/United_Airlines).

#### Subway and passenger trains

The [Washington Metro](/Washington_Metro) subway system, the second-busiest in the nation, provides transit, with an expansion reaching [Dulles International Airport](/Dulles_International_Airport). The [Virginia Railway Express (VRE)](/Virginia_Railway_Express) offers commuter rail service. Local [transit bus](/Transit_bus) services are also available.

#### Highways

Traffic congestion is a significant issue, with Northern Virginia hosting several of the nation's worst [bottlenecks](/Traffic_bottleneck). Major highways include I-495 (the [Capital Beltway](/Interstate_495_(Capital_Beltway))), I-95, I-395, and I-66. [High-occupancy vehicle (HOV)](/High-occupancy_vehicle) lanes are implemented on several routes. The region is also developing [Express Lanes](/Express_Lanes) requiring an [E-ZPass](/E-ZPass) for toll payment.

Major infrastructure projects like the reconstruction of the [Springfield Interchange](/Springfield_Interchange) and [Woodrow Wilson Bridge](/Woodrow_Wilson_Bridge] have been completed, but Potomac River crossings remain choke points. High housing costs contribute to long commutes from outer counties and neighboring states, exacerbating traffic. Restrictive zoning in some areas also forces development into outer counties, increasing travel distances.

### Education

Northern Virginia boasts a strong educational system.

#### Primary education

[Fairfax County Public Schools](/Fairfax_County_Public_Schools) is highly regarded, particularly its [Thomas Jefferson High School for Science and Technology](/Thomas_Jefferson_High_School_for_Science_and_Technology), consistently ranked among the nation's best.

#### Colleges and universities

[George Mason University](/George_Mason_University) in [Fairfax, Virginia](/Fairfax,_Virginia) is the largest public university in the state by enrollment. Other institutions include [Northern Virginia Community College](/Northern_Virginia_Community_College) (NOVA), [University of Mary Washington](/University_of_Mary_Washington) in [Fredericksburg, Virginia](/Fredericksburg,_Virginia), [Patrick Henry College](/Patrick_Henry_College) in western Loudoun County, and [Marymount University](/Marymount_University) in Arlington. Satellite campuses of [University of Virginia](/University_of_Virginia), [Virginia Tech](/Virginia_Tech), and [George Washington University](/George_Washington_University) are also present.

